<figureCitation id="6BE58A04D96CF2D4E71070A1E6606140" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Photos of Miconia lima (A-E) and Miconia pagnolensis (F). A Miconia lima from Massif de la Selle, Haiti showing habit and ascending stem hairs (Majure 4334) B expanded infloresence and flowers showing whitish-pink petals (Sierra de Bahoruco, DR; Skean 4312), C-E) &quot; Monteada Nueva &quot; form of Miconia lima from the Dominican Republic C habit, inflorescence structure and stem showing ascending hairs (Majure 5960) D flower with dark pink petals showing an thers with a dorso-basal appendage and immature fruit with pinkish calyx lobes E leaf adaxial surface and stem with ascending hairs (D-E from Judd 8083) F Miconia pagnolensis sp. nov. from the type specimen showing habit and bulla-based hairs of the adaxial leaf surface (Timyan 27). Photos A and C taken by L. C. Majure, B by J. D. Skean, Jr., D-E by W. S. Judd and F by J. Timyan." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.72.9355.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/106473" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Fig. 20F</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
